            },
            "secId": "se0120",
            "sentence": "This proposition, together with the main results of [BLGGT, Theorem 4.2.1, Corollary 4.5.2], we have the following automorphy lifting and potential automorphy results.",
            "startOffset": 318166,
            "title": "Applications to automorphy lifting theorem and potential automorphy theorem"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 265116,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0010": {
                    "endOffset": 265115,
                    "startOffset": 265108
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Currently, one of the strongest available statements is given in [BLGGT], where an automorphy lifting theorem has been established under some mild condition in the case where the Galois representation, restricted to the decomposition group at each prime dividing p, is \u201cpotentially diagonalizable\u201d in the sense of [BLGGT].",
            "startOffset": 264794,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 270955,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0080": {
                    "endOffset": 270954,
                    "startOffset": 270949
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Our family is a generalization of the family constructed in [BLZ].",
            "startOffset": 270889,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 265269,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "However, the notion of potential diagonalizability is defined in terms of a universal deformation ring whose structure has not yet been well-understood.",
            "startOffset": 265117,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 313602,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0110",
            "sentence": "\u25a1",
            "startOffset": 313601,
            "title": "Local deformation rings and moduli of Wach modules"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 270763,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Let us give a brief summary of the structure of the paper.",
            "startOffset": 270705,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 303547,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "se0090",
                    "title": "The representation of type (w,(ri,\u03be),(\u03b1i,\u03be))"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "se0100",
            "sentence": "Below we prove the \u201cconverse\u201d part.",
            "startOffset": 303512,
            "title": "Semi-induced representations"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 303626,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "se0090",
                    "title": "The representation of type (w,(ri,\u03be),(\u03b1i,\u03be))"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "se0100",
            "sentence": "The other part is easier to prove and follows by reversing the argument below.",
            "startOffset": 303548,
            "title": "Semi-induced representations"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 271245,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0170": {
                    "endOffset": 271107,
                    "startOffset": 271100
                },
                "br0180": {
                    "endOffset": 271107,
                    "startOffset": 271100
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "In Section 4, we recall the deformation rings introduced by Kisin [K2,K3] and check that the family of nearly semi-induced representations are contained in one connected component of the local deformation space.",
            "startOffset": 271034,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 271033,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "In Section 3, we introduce the notion of nearly semi-induced representations.",
            "startOffset": 270956,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 271337,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "In Section 5, we describe some applications to automorphy lifting and potential automorphy.",
            "startOffset": 271246,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 270888,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0030": {
                    "endOffset": 270887,
                    "startOffset": 270883
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "In Section 2, we construct a certain family of Galois representations by using the theory of Wach modules developed in [B1].",
            "startOffset": 270764,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 309345,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0110",
            "sentence": "In this section, we study universal family of Wach modules, local deformation rings, and subfamily corresponding to the family constructed in the previous section.",
            "startOffset": 309182,
            "title": "Local deformation rings and moduli of Wach modules"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 313599,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0180": {
                    "endOffset": 313598,
                    "startOffset": 313577
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0110",
            "sentence": "This is a special case of [K3, Theorem (3.3.8)].",
            "startOffset": 313551,
            "title": "Local deformation rings and moduli of Wach modules"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 265638,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Owing to this, potential diagonalizability is in some sense like a tautological synonym for the local condition with which we can manage to show an automorphy of a global Galois representation by the currently available methods, and it seems that we do not have a description of the potentially diagonalizable representations which is concrete enough for applications.",
            "startOffset": 265270,
            "title": "Introduction"
        }
